[
    {
        "content": "<p>True or false: the mathlib definition <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/nondiscrete_normed_field\">docs#nondiscrete_normed_field</a> implies characteristic zero?</p>",
        "id": 221370537,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1609537583
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I hope it's false so that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>p</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}_p((t))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.036108em;vertical-align:-0.286108em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15139200000000003em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.286108em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> can have the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.61508em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>-adic norm...</p>",
        "id": 221370748,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609537924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have no idea what that is :) Does it satisfy our definition?</p>",
        "id": 221370776,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1609537984
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think <code>zmod 2</code> is a normed_field, where the distance between 0 and 1 is 1</p>",
        "id": 221370939,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538246
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah I think so. The name \"non discrete\" is unfortunate, because the norm on the field I mentioned comes from a <em>discrete</em> valuation</p>",
        "id": 221370941,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110049\">Mario Carneiro</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/algebra.20problem/near/221370939\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think <code>zmod 2</code> is a normed_field, where the distance between 0 and 1 is 1</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, but the <code>nondiscrete</code> hypothesis excludes that example.</p>",
        "id": 221370952,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1609538274
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"non-discrete\" should really be called \"non-trivial\"</p>",
        "id": 221371017,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538347
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, that assumption implies that it is at least infinite</p>",
        "id": 221371023,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538361
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or \"non-trivially-normed\" field</p>",
        "id": 221371024,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538369
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Adam, your example is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>p</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}_p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.974998em;vertical-align:-0.286108em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15139200000000003em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.286108em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-coefficient rational functions in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.61508em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>?  What is the norm?</p>",
        "id": 221371035,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1609538389
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's Laurent series. The norm sends t to 1/2 (for example)</p>",
        "id": 221371078,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538412
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what happens with the padic norm on Qp?</p>",
        "id": 221371087,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538439
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Same. But that char 0</p>",
        "id": 221371092,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538449
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The same norm works for rational functions</p>",
        "id": 221371105,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538485
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>aha, now I'm on board with adam's example</p>",
        "id": 221371196,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538607
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does it work with rational functions?</p>",
        "id": 221371197,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538617
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah</p>",
        "id": 221371199,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538625
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example you can embed rational functions in Laurent series and restrict the norm</p>",
        "id": 221371243,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538643
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what's the norm exactly? Is it the degree?</p>",
        "id": 221371244,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Explicitly the norm of a power series in t is (1/2)^n where n is the index of the first coefficient of the series which is nonzero</p>",
        "id": 221371252,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538699
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(1/2 is of course a choice, and you can choose any positive real less than 1)</p>",
        "id": 221371260,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538722
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>or greater</p>",
        "id": 221371262,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1609538732
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, it needs to be less than 1</p>",
        "id": 221371269,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538750
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The triangle inequality won't work otherwise</p>",
        "id": 221371272,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609538758
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, if you want to work with rational functions then it doesn't matter, since you can always replace t with 1/t, but for Laurent series one should be careful</p>",
        "id": 221371500,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1609539092
    }
]